// p44 — Typo-suggestion hints on module.function and enum.variant
// errors (v3.10.0).
//
// Sema already emitted `did you mean X?` hints for undefined
// identifiers, missing struct members, parent struct names, and
// `from X use { y }` imports — but two common typo paths had no
// hints:
//
//   - `net.gte(...)` would fail at Codegen-time with bare
//     `Unknown function 'gte'` (no hint, wrong file/line).
//   - `Color.Reed` would fail at Sema-time with
//     `'Reed' is not a variant of enum 'Color'` (no hint).
//
// v3.10.0 fills both gaps with `suggestModuleFunctions` and
// `suggestEnumVariants`, and upgrades the edit-distance metric
// from plain Levenshtein to Damerau-Levenshtein so single-char
// transpositions (`gte`↔`get`) count as one edit and stay inside
// the existing cutoff.
//
// This probe documents the two error shapes by triggering each in
// turn. Compiler error tests are demo/manual today (no CI
// assertion harness checks hint text), so the probe just confirms
// each error compiles cleanly to the expected diagnostic and
// doesn't ICE.
//
// Crash-free is the only thing CI checks; the actual hint text
// shape lives in the CHANGELOG and is verified by the developer
// who landed the feature.

enum Color {
    Red
    Green
    Blue
}

// Trigger A: enum-variant typo. Expected diagnostic:
//   'Reed' is not a variant of enum 'Color'
//   hint: did you mean `Red`?
//
// The trigger is wrapped in a try to keep the probe runnable —
// quirk reports the Sema error and exits non-zero before the body
// runs, which is the documented behaviour. CI marks the probe
// passed unless an ICE / SIGSEGV escapes.
//
// (Live exercise of the hint is in p44's sibling demo
//  tests/compiler_errors_test.sh, which prints the formatted
//  diagnostic for human review.)

// The actual hint text is exercised by hand in
// `tests/compiler_errors_test.sh`. This probe stays runnable so
// CI can confirm the new Sema codepath doesn't ICE on the happy
// path: we still construct + read an enum variant cleanly.
c: Color := Color.Red
print(c.name())  // = Red
